   "source": [
    "## 🧠 7.5.1: The Scaled Dot-Product Math\n",
    "\n",
    "### 🧪 Discovery Lab: The Vanishing Gradient & Attention Explosion\n",
    "\n",
    "Suppose we have high-dimensional query ($Q$) and key ($K$) representation vectors. If their dimension $d_k$ is large (e.g., $d_k = 64$), the raw dot products can evaluate to large values (e.g. $80.0$). Let's see what happens if we pass unscaled scores to Softmax.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 1. The Naive Attempt (Unscaled Attention)\n",
    "We calculate the raw dot product scores and pass them straight into the softmax function:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import math\n",
    "from typing import List\n",
    "\n",
    "def softmax(logits: List[float]) -> List[float]:\n",
    "    exp_logits = [math.exp(z) for z in logits]\n",
    "    sum_exp = sum(exp_logits)\n",
    "    return [e / sum_exp for e in exp_logits]\n",
    "\n",
    "raw_scores = [80.0, 2.0, -5.0]\n",
    "try:\n",
    "    probs = softmax(raw_scores)\n",
    "    print(f\"Unscaled Attention Weights: {probs}\")\n",
    "except OverflowError as e:\n",
    "    print(f\"CRASHED due to exponential explosion: {e}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "#### 2. The Mathematical Necessity\n",
    "Under unscaled scores, the softmax distribution spikes to a binary state (`1.0` for the largest, `0.0` for all others). The model loses the capacity to distribute attention smoothly or backpropagate gradients. It becomes mathematically \"blind.\"\n",
    "\n",
    "To solve this, we divide the dot product by the **square root of the key dimension $\\sqrt{d_k}$** before passing to softmax:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\text{Scaled Score} = \\frac{Q \\cdot K}{\\sqrt{d_k}}$$\n",
    "\n",
    "#### 3. The Rosetta Stone (Scaled Dot-Product Attention)\n",
    "$$\\text{Attention}(Q, K, V) = \\text{Softmax}\\left(\\frac{Q K^T}{\\sqrt{d_k}}\\right) V$$"
   ]
  },
